<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-10-17T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-10-17T19:00:00-05:00" n="323" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d323">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">882.00/852: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Reber</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-10-17T19:00:00-05:00">October 17, 1930—7
                                p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>89. Your 144, October 16, noon. If the British Chargé in Liberia deems it
                            advisable to request a British warship, and if the British Government
                            decides to send such a vessel, I do not perceive any objection to this
                            course. You may inform your British colleague accordingly.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>